I used to live across the street from this cafe back when those buildings were artist-only lofts controlled by the Podmajersky Group. While I do recall the owner of Krisoffer's getting persnickety with me about trying to use a debit card for purchases just slightly under $10, that was over decade ago, and whenever I pass through Chi-town I always -assuming they're open- try swing by for a coffee and one of their chocoflanes. Their cakes really are second to none as the Midwest, and in particular the Pilsen neighborhood of Chicago, proffers some of the best Mexican selections you're going to find. Kristoffer's banana-wrapped tamales also come recommended. Definitely worth a stop if you're cruising down Halsted through Pilsen East.

The caramel tres leches cake was amazing! Even after days in the fridge, the leftover slices kept the same taste,  'structural integrity' and moistness as the day we got it. We called the day before to reserve our cake, they don't have many whole cakes at hand but they do have a variety of slices available and we got a slice of vanilla chocolate tres leches (only because they didn't have the chocolate flan cake), cold horchata latte and hot mexican coffee when picking up our birthday cake. They do have a savory menu of sandwiches and such, which we did not try. It's a cozy mom and pop bakeshop with a couch area and a few cafe style tables & chairs. The north 8 bus stop is right in front - very accessible on the CTA, parking is on the streets and it's an $10 uberX ride to lakeshore east area. If you're in the area or have a craving for quality tres leches cake, give them a try.

A cozy little bakery with tres leches cake. On a recommendation, we tried the cakes from Kristoffer's.  Together we tried: Vanilla (with chocolate frosting) Kahlua (with vanilla frosting) Caramel (with a caramel glaze) ChocoFlan (chocolate cake on top of flan)  We were a bit disappointed that the cakes were all a bit dry. But that may have been from the edge of the cake being a little too dry. If you simply ate the cake without getting a bite of the edge, it was pretty moist (as it well should be for a Tres Leches cake!). I think the consensus favorite was the chocoflan, because there was now frosting or glaze, just cake and flan.  Other flavors of Tres Leches available: Chocolate (all chocolate cake) Coconut
